<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-571-026  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 571 026.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 18 1990 v24 n25 p104(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tearing down export walls. (Industry Insight) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pastore, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Eastern European computer users are facing a wall of governmentalred tape regarding export control policy and technology transferissues.andP;  Analysts note that the US currently lags behind in theeasing of these restrictions, which were formulated under 'coldwar' conditions.andP;  A recent easing of export restrictions on thepart of the Coordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls(Cocom) is a step forward, but more needs to be done to takeadvantage of the unique opportunity for marketing US computertechnology.andP;  If this is not done, potential buyers will turnincreasingly to competitors in Western Europe and Japan to buy thehardware they need to build up their economies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersExportTechnology TransferEastern EuropeCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsGovernment RegulationInternational TradeCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>